Document Review & Corrections (v1.1)

Reviewed 2026-05-14. Strategic and requirements content preserved; the following corrections apply and override earlier text where they conflict.

1. Commercial model (new requirement). AirportFaster is merchant of record: it collects the full customer payment via Stripe and settles suppliers separately (DECISIONS.md D-006). This adds requirements for a settlements ledger, supplier payout tracking, and tax-handling readiness in the Finance module.

2. Charge timing (new requirement). The customer is charged at checkout, not on supplier confirmation (D-007). Refund flows are therefore MVP-critical.

3. Pricing engine (clarification). The pricing engine must support, per airport/service row, either a fixed AirportFaster price or supplier cost + markup (D-008). "Future dynamic pricing logic" remains post-MVP and refers to AI/algorithmic pricing only.

4. Payment provider. Stripe is the canonical provider for all payment requirements in section 17 (Payment Intents, webhooks with signature validation, multi-currency, refunds, partial refunds, reconciliation). See D-001.

5. Roles (section 12). The canonical set is seven roles — add Analyst (read-only analytics/reports) to the six listed.

6. AI draft systems are in MVP. The AI SEO draft system and AI translation draft system are MVP scope (draft-only; never auto-publish). Only fully automated AI operations are post-MVP.

7. Tech stack. Canonical: Fastify (not Express), Prisma (ORM), PostgreSQL, Redis, S3-compatible storage, Sentry, PostHog, OpenAI API.

8. The Database Architecture & Entity Relationship Design document (previously missing) now exists and is the data-layer source of truth.